infobox.casualties1:
'''total military casualties:'''&lt;br /&gt;1,000,000+
{{collapsible list
|title = breakdown
|'''casualties of 1941:'''
&lt;hr/&gt;
according to [[german army (wehrmacht)|german army]] medical reports (including [[army of norway (wehrmacht)|army norway]]):{{sfn|askey|2014|p=178}}
* 186,452 killed
* 40,157 missing
* 655,179 wounded in action{{efn|excludes an additional 395,799 who were deemed unfit for service due to non-combat causes, transported out of their army group sectors for treatment, and treated in divisional/local medical facilities. 98% of those 395,799 eventually returned to active duty service, usually after relatively short treatment, meaning about 8,000 became permanent losses. askey 2014, p. 178.}}
* 8,000 evacuated sick
&lt;hr/&gt;
* 2,827 aircraft destroyed{{sfn|bergström|2007|p=117}}
* 2,735 tanks destroyed{{sfn|liedtke|2016|p=220}}{{sfn|askey|2014|p=185}}
* 104 assault guns destroyed{{sfn|liedtke|2016|p=220}}{{sfn|askey|2014|p=185}}
&lt;hr/&gt;
'''other involved country losses'''
* {{flagicon|rou}} 114,000+ casualties (at least 39,000 dead or missing){{efn|see: mark axworthy, ''third axis fourth ally: romanian armed forces in the european war, 1941–1945''. pages 58 and 286.}}
* {{flagicon|kingdom of italy}} 8,700 casualties{{efn|see:robert kirchubel. ''operation barbarossa: the german invasion of soviet russia''. bloomsbury publishing. chapter: &quot;opposing armies&quot;.}}
* {{flagicon|fin}} 5,000+ casualties{{efn|includes only finnish casualties in northern finland during operation silver fox.{{sfn|ziemke|1959|p=184}}}}
}}

